Suppose I select the four squares: (1,1), (1,2), (2,2), (3,2). Let's see. Horizontal rectangles: Row 1: (1,1)-(1,2): yes, (1,1) and (1,2) are both selected. Covered. Row 2: (2,1)-(2,2): (2,1) not selected, but (2,2) is selected. Covered. Row 2: (2,2)-(2,3): yes, (2,2) is selected. Covered. Row 3: (3,2)-(3,3): yes, (3,2) is selected. Covered. Row 3: (3,1)-(3,2): (3,1) not selected, but (3,2) is selected. Covered. Vertical rectangles: Column 1: (1,1)-(2,1): (1,1) is selected. Covered. Column 1: (2,1)-(3,1): not covered, since (2,1) and (3,1) are not selected. Column 2: (1,2)-(2,2): both selected. Covered. Column 2: (2,2)-(3,2): both selected. Covered. Column 3: (1,3)-(2,3): not covered, since neither (1,3) nor (2,3) is selected. Column 3: (2,3)-(3,3): (2,3) not selected, (3,3) not selected. Not covered. So this selection of 4 squares misses the vertical rectangles in column 1 and column 3, and the horizontal rectangle in row 3's left part. So it's not sufficient. Row 3: (3,2)-(3,3): no. Row 3: (3,1)-(3,2): yes. So horizontal rectangles in rows 1,2,3 are covered. Vertical rectangles: Column 1: (1,1)-(2,1): yes. Column 1: (2,1
